hands_on_practices.problem:
Consider the infinite series $\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} a_n$ where the terms $a_n$ are defined for integers $n \geq 1$ as follows:
$$
a_n = \begin{cases}
    \frac{1}{(n+1)^2} & \text{if } n \text{ is odd} \\
    \frac{1}{(n-1)^2} & \text{if } n \text{ is even}
\end{cases}
$$
This series is constructed such that its terms are not monotonically decreasing. Determine if the series converges, and if it does, compute its sum. You are given the value of the sum for the Basel problem: $\sum_{k=1}^{\infty} \frac{1}{k^2} = \frac{\pi^2}{6}$.

Express your final answer as a symbolic expression in terms of $\pi$.
